package compose:host@0.1.0;

/// Smoke-test interface used only by the wasm-orchestrator proof of
/// concept. NOT part of the stable host surface. Will be removed once
/// the orchestrator exports real `sys:compose` interfaces.
interface smoke {
    /// Call into `runtime-info.get-fingerprint` and return the
    /// host's reported runtime name. Used to verify import wiring
    /// from a wasm guest to a native host.
    host-name: func() -> string;

    /// Compute the SHA-256 digest of `bytes` by calling into
    /// `compose-core`'s digest function from inside the wasm
    /// component. Used to verify that the orchestrator's pure-Rust
    /// logic is reachable from a wasm guest — i.e. that compose-core
    /// genuinely compiles and runs as part of the orchestrator
    /// component, not just as a Rust library on the native host.
    digest: func(bytes: list<u8>) -> list<u8>;

    /// Write `count` audit entries for a tenant through compose-core's
    /// AuditLogger, backed by the composed secure-log component (via
    /// the imported `secure-log:log/log`), then verify the tenant's
    /// hash chain. Returns the head sequence number on success.
    ///
    /// Proves end-to-end that the wasm orchestrator drives a
    /// tamper-evident audit log through component composition — the
    /// same AuditLogger code that runs natively, over a WIT-imported
    /// secure-log backend.
    audit-demo: func(tenant: string, count: u32) -> result<u64, string>;

    /// Diagnostic probe for the `host:bootstrap` and
    /// `tegmentum:runtime` imports the world declares.
    ///
    /// - Reads `host:bootstrap.args` and reports the argument count.
    /// - Constructs (and immediately drops) a `tegmentum:runtime/
    ///   control.runtime` with default limits, to prove the runtime
    ///   frontend is reachable from this component.
    ///
    /// Returns a short diagnostic string on success (e.g. `"args=2
    /// runtime=ok"`) or a `result::err` if either import failed —
    /// which most commonly means the outer embedder did not provide
    /// a `tegmentum:runtime` implementation.
    ///
    /// Not called in the normal `sys:compose/*` hot path. Its
    /// purpose is to keep both imports referenced from Rust code so
    /// dead-code elimination does not strip them from the compiled
    /// component. That way `wasm-tools component wit` reports the
    /// declared imports even before the composer's other code paths
    /// use them.
    tegmentum-probe: func() -> result<string, string>;
}
